<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About GE washer repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">GE washers are durable workhorses across SoCal, and the control board solder-joint pattern is the service issue we see most often.</h2>

    <p>GE Appliances (the laundry, refrigeration, and cooking division) was sold by General Electric to Haier in 2016 for $5.4 billion. Operationally, GE Appliances still runs as a US business unit headquartered in Louisville, Kentucky, with most engineering and manufacturing concentrated at Appliance Park, one of the largest appliance plants in North America. From a parts-and-service standpoint, the Haier transition has been seamless: OEM parts availability is unchanged, the Louisville KY supply chain is intact, and most service items we order arrive within 1-3 days from authorized GE distribution.</p>

    <p>GE washers split cleanly into two architectures. <strong>GTW-series</strong> are top-load washers, common across rental properties, builder-grade homes, and value-tier installations throughout our service area. <strong>GFW-series</strong> are front-load washers, common in renovation kitchens and stackable laundry rooms across the Westside and Pasadena. Both share a common pattern: <strong>main control board solder-joint failures</strong> at year 5-9. Solder joints crack from years of thermal cycling, and the symptoms range from intermittent function loss to all-lights-blinking lockouts. Replacement runs $345-$525 with labor.</p>

    <p>One service detail most LA shops botch on GE board work: <strong>personality programming</strong>. GE top-load washers share the same board hardware across many models, so a replacement board must be programmed to the correct model "personality", features don't work right if this step is skipped. Cycle options, SmartDispense linkage, sensor calibration, and timing all depend on the personality being set correctly. We perform programming as part of every GE board swap at no extra labor charge. If you've ever heard of a GE washer that "got a new board but doesn't work right", that's almost always the personality step that was missed.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 COMMON PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Common GE washer problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we see fail most often on GE washers, and how we diagnose each.</h2>

    <p class="lead">GE washer service calls cluster around five symptom categories. Each has a predictable diagnostic tree we follow before quoting parts.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Won't drain (no error code or vague drain error):</strong> About 40% resolve at the debris filter clear (GFW front-load) or drain hose check (GTW top-load), no parts cost. Remaining 60% are drain pump replacements ($245-$385).</li>
      <li><strong>All control panel lights blinking / no response:</strong> Door or lid lock fault first (the lock has to engage before any cycle starts), then control board solder-joint failure. Lock replacement $145-$245; board replacement $345-$525 (with personality programming included). About 60% resolve at lock; 40% are board.</li>
      <li><strong>Won't start with full panel functional (top-load GTW):</strong> Lid switch failure year 3-6, most common GTW service item. The lid switch is what tells the controls the lid is closed; failure causes the dryer to refuse to start even though everything looks normal. $145-$215 replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Water leaking from the door (front-load GFW):</strong> Door boot / bellows seal tear. Year 7-9 wear item. The boot accumulates debris, mildew, and tears from repeated flex. Bellows replacement $285-$425, sealant doesn't fix a torn boot.</li>
      <li><strong>Loud rumble or grinding during spin (front-load GFW):</strong> Shock absorber wear (pair) $185-$285, year 6-8 service item. Less commonly, drum bearing, full bearing service runs $585-$880 and on a 10+ year GFW often pencils out as replacement rather than repair.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>GE Profile washers add SmartDispense automatic detergent dispensing, when the dispenser pump itself fails (year 6-9, $185-$285), the symptom is "no detergent in cycle" rather than a fault code. We test the dispenser pump on every Profile diagnostic if the customer reports detergent issues.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 CONTROL BOARDS DEEP-DIVE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03, GE washer control boards</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The control board solder-joint pattern, and why "personality programming" matters.</h2>

    <p>GE washer control boards have a documented pattern of solder-joint failure on certain components, specifically resistors and relays that handle motor and pump switching. The failure mode: a solder joint cracks from thermal cycling over years of operation, the affected component loses contact intermittently, and the symptoms progress from "occasional weird behavior" to outright function loss. Year 5-9 is the most common window across both GTW and GFW.</p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Symptoms of a failing GE washer board</h3>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>All control panel lights blinking on power-up with no response to button presses</li>
      <li>Cycle starts but stops mid-cycle without a clear error code</li>
      <li>One specific function (spin, drain, or specific cycle option) doesn't work while others do</li>
      <li>Random cycle selection or display showing wrong cycle</li>
      <li>Won't power on at all (full board failure, distinguishable from a failed door switch by checking line voltage at the board input)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="subhead">The personality programming problem</h3>
    <p>Here's the detail that separates a quality GE board repair from a botched one. <strong>GE top-load washers share the same physical board hardware across multiple model variants.</strong> The same board powers GTW680BSJWS, GTW720BSNWS, GTW750CPLDG, and several other models, but each model needs different cycle programming, sensor calibration, and feature linkage. After installation, the board must be programmed to the correct model "personality" using GE's authorized service tool. This step takes about 5-10 minutes and is part of the OEM service procedure, but shops without the proper programming tool sometimes skip it.</p>

    <p>What happens if personality programming is skipped: the washer technically powers on with the new board, but cycle options work incorrectly (heavy duty might run as normal, sensor cycles might never sense properly), SmartDispense doesn't link to the cycle on Profile units, and sometimes specific cycles flat-out don't work. <strong>We perform personality programming as part of every GE board replacement</strong>, it's not a separate line item, it's part of the repair. If you've ever heard of a GE washer "getting a new board but still not working right," that's almost always the personality step.</p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Diagnostic before board replacement</h3>
    <p>We don't quote a board until the obvious alternatives are ruled out. Failed door/lid lock, blown line fuse on the board (separate cheaper repair), bad wiring harness connection, or stuck membrane keypad button can all mimic board failure. About 25% of "I think it's the board" calls turn out to be one of those simpler items at significantly lower cost.</p>
  </div>
</section>

