    <h2 class="section-title">Two jobs from across the territory.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Representative service calls, model, symptom, diagnosis, repair, and cost. Names and addresses omitted; technical scenarios are typical of GE washer service across each environment.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>GE GFW490RPK0DG front-load, Sherman Oaks</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> All control panel lights blinking on power-up; washer wouldn't start any cycle. Customer had been quoted $580 for "control board replacement" by another shop without diagnostic visit.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Standard GFW blinking-light diagnostic order. Verified door lock engagement on closing, lock motor cycled on closing but didn't fully engage the latch. Tested door lock motor: drawing current but mechanical jam in the latch mechanism. Door lock confirmed as the failure, not the control board.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Replaced door lock assembly with OEM GE part (in stock on the truck for GFW490 generation). Verified normal cycle operation through full test cycle including high-speed spin.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $215 total. Same-day, completed in 75 minutes. Saved customer $365 versus the misdiagnosed board quote.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>GE GTW680BSJWS top-load, Riverside</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Cycle would start but stop mid-cycle randomly. No error code displayed. Customer had been ignoring it for two months.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Tested all simple alternatives first, lid switch (good), water valve (good), drain hose (clear). Connected GE service tool to the board diagnostic port; pulled error history. Board reported intermittent motor relay failure consistent with the GE solder-joint pattern at year 7. Confirmed by visual inspection of the board after removal, visible solder crack on the motor relay terminal.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Replaced main control board with new OEM GE part. <strong>Programmed the board to GTW680BSJWS personality</strong> using GE service tool, 8 minutes. Verified all cycle options functional, sensor wash sensing properly, SmartDispense linkage correct. Customer informed that personality programming had been performed as part of the swap.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $485 total. Same-day, completed in 2 hours including programming and full-cycle verification.</p>
